******
[2] Michigan
Date: Thu 30 Aug 2012
Source: Fox17, WXMI-TV [edited]
http://www.fox17online.com/news/fox17-deer-disease-found-in-west-michigan-20120830,0,285204.story


Wild white-tailed deer in 17 Michigan counties are reportedly infected by epizootic hemorrhagic disease (EHD), according to officials with the Michigan Department of Agriculture and Rural Development (MDARD) and Michigan State University's (MSU) Diagnostic Center for Population and Animal Health (DPAH).

EHD is contracted most often by wild white-tailed deer, but was reported in domesticated deer in 2006. It is not transmissible to humans, but is an acute, infectious, and fatal disease caused by biting midges, which primarily impacts cervids (deer), a news release stated.

"This is not a coincidence," said State Veterinarian Dr Steven L Halstead. "Owners of cervid (deer) facilities should make themselves aware of EHD cases occurring in wild white-tailed deer in Michigan and other states and take measures to manage biting insects around these valuable animals."

EHD is transmitted via blood feeding midges. The disease cannot be transmitted from one animal to another by direct contact, a news release stated. EHD is typically detected in wild white-tailed deer in late summer and early fall. Large die offs of up to 100 animals have been reported, often near water because EHD causes high fever and dehydration, MDARD warned. Deer will appear sluggish, lame, confused, and unresponsive to humans. At times, the deer may even have discharge from the nose and sores in their mouths along with a swollen tongue.

The 17 counties affected include: Allegan, Barry, Berrien, Branch, Calhoun, Cass, Clinton, Eaton, Gratiot, Ionia, Jackson, Kent, Montcalm, Muskegon, Ottawa, Shiawassee, and St Joseph, the MDARD stated. Two privately owned cervid (POC) facilities in Barry and Ionia Counties have confirmed cases.

[Byline: Leigh Ann Towne]

