******
[3] Michigan
Date: Sun 2 Sep 2012
Source: The Morning Sun [edited]
http://www.themorningsun.com/article/20120902/NEWS/120909923/disease-outbreak-continues-to-kill-white-tailed-deer


The disease, epizootic hemorrhagic disease [EHD], increases the pulse, respiration rates, and body temperature of white-tailed deer before they enter a shock-like state and die. Deer usually exhibit these symptoms roughly a week after exposure.

According to 28 Aug 2012 report from the Michigan Department of Natural Resources [DNR], 1762 total white-tailed deer have been infected by EHD. Most of the cases are confined to Michigan's southern counties. The Ionia County deer population has been hit particularly hard by the virus, with over 1100 confirmed deaths from EHD. More than 200 deer have been reported dead from the disease inside Ionia County lines for each of the past 4 weeks. Branch County has seen the 2nd-biggest EHD outbreak, with 225 confirmed infections from EHD. Clinton County has confirmed 153 cases of EHD, though 97 cases were observed in the DNR's latest report alone. Calhoun, Gratiot, Barry, Allegan, and Cass counties have all confirmed double-digit deer deaths from EHD infections, and several other counties have seen a small number of infected deer.

According to the Michigan Department of Natural Resources, there is no known treatment for the disease, though there is no evidence that would suggest humans can be infected. The disease is transmitted by insects carrying the virus. No other source of transmission is known except for a bite from a biological vector. The most common vector, the insect _Culicoides variipennis_, dies off come late autumn. The DNR expects the disease to die abruptly after the swarming insects fail to outlast the frost.

An estimated 2150 deaths in the Michigan white-tailed deer population have been observed since 1955. This year's [2012] outbreak has already accounted for more than 80 percent of that number. The DNR stated that EHD can have a significant effect on a local deer population, though statewide decreases of population have never been observed.

Other symptoms infected deer exhibit include loss of appetite, weakness, salivation, and unconsciousness. Those killed by the virus are often found by bodies of water to soothe themselves from fever.

[Byline: David Oltean]

